729
00:40:06,640 --> 00:40:11,580
An AI will give you an answer that is entirely factually wrong, but it will write it with the

730
00:40:11,580 --> 00:40:15,120
supreme authoritative confidence of a tenured professor.

731
00:40:15,360 --> 00:40:15,620
Why?

732
00:40:15,860 --> 00:40:21,700
Because its training data consisted of authoritative human texts, textbooks, published papers,

733
00:40:21,880 --> 00:40:24,700
encyclopedias, which usually correlate with being right.

734
00:40:25,060 --> 00:40:27,900
The model collapsed confidence into correctness.

735
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:30,240
F of correct became F of confident.

736
00:40:30,380 --> 00:40:31,160
So how do you fix it?

737
00:40:31,180 --> 00:40:32,880
You don't penalize it for sounding confident.

738
00:40:33,200 --> 00:40:35,920
Based on Flyxion's theory, you have to demonstrate the empty fiber.

739
00:40:36,100 --> 00:40:40,940
You have to feed it training examples of highly confident prose that is completely undeniably

740
00:40:40,940 --> 00:40:42,060
factually wrong.

741
00:40:42,240 --> 00:40:43,880
You have to break the proxy identity.

742
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:46,860
You have to show it that the two variables are orthogonal.

743
00:40:47,420 --> 00:40:48,400
Or take the next prediction.

744
00:40:48,520 --> 00:40:50,160
Long arguments do not equal thoroughness.

745
00:40:50,160 --> 00:40:54,000
Just because an AI writes a massive essay doesn't mean it covers all the bases.

746
00:40:54,200 --> 00:40:56,100
It might just be repeating itself or padding.

747
00:40:56,500 --> 00:40:56,920
The fix.

748
00:40:57,600 --> 00:41:01,200
Show it short, ironclad, comprehensive arguments.

749
00:41:01,760 --> 00:41:04,100
Show it brevity that is conceptually perfect.

750
00:41:04,320 --> 00:41:05,280
And the final prediction.

751
00:41:06,180 --> 00:41:08,080
Formal language does not equal precision.

752
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:14,620
An AI might use massive vocabulary and formal syntax, but be logically incredibly sloppy.

753
00:41:14,620 --> 00:41:17,140
Because it learned that smart people use big words.

754
00:41:17,720 --> 00:41:23,580
The fix is to show it highly informal conversational language that is laser precise in its logic.

755
00:41:23,980 --> 00:41:26,800
Show it slang that cuts perfectly to the core of an issue.

756
00:41:27,080 --> 00:41:30,420
What Flyxion is doing here is redefining the true measure of intelligence.

757
00:41:31,200 --> 00:41:34,580
The tech world right now is obsessed with entropy reduction making models

758
00:41:34,580 --> 00:41:39,100
that spit out highly predictable, highly confident, highly structured text.

759
00:41:39,480 --> 00:41:43,180
But the measure of an intelligent system is not its ability to reduce uncertainty.

760
00:41:43,180 --> 00:41:46,420
It is its ability to preserve the distinctions that matter.

761
00:41:47,100 --> 00:41:48,720
Thinking longer is not thinking better.

762
00:41:48,960 --> 00:41:51,260
Writing more formally is not thinking more clearly.

763
00:41:51,660 --> 00:41:55,100
When a system learns that the appearance of hard work and the substance of hard work

764
00:41:55,100 --> 00:41:58,900
are not the same thing, that is when true, robust capability emerges.

765
00:41:59,340 --> 00:42:02,800
Which makes me want to ask you, the listener, a direct question right now.

766
00:42:03,420 --> 00:42:06,480
Where are you applying the wrong proxies in your own life?

767
00:42:06,960 --> 00:42:11,720
Where are you jutting the substance of something entirely by its accidents

768
00:42:11,720 --> 00:42:14,100
simply because of the environment you're used to?

769
00:42:14,180 --> 00:42:15,200
It's a great question to ask.

770
00:42:15,280 --> 00:42:20,200
Are you assuming someone is a good leader just because they speak loudly in meetings?

771
00:42:20,940 --> 00:42:25,260
Are you assuming a project is valuable just because it took 100 hours to complete?

772
00:42:26,140 --> 00:42:28,840
The geometry of verbosity isn't just in the AI.

773
00:42:29,160 --> 00:42:31,320
It's in our own representations of reality.

774
00:42:31,720 --> 00:42:34,120
We all have collapsed fibers that need repairing.

775
00:42:34,120 --> 00:42:36,640
It is the human condition to rely on proxies.

776
00:42:36,820 --> 00:42:37,900
They're efficient shortcuts.

777
00:42:38,320 --> 00:42:42,500
But it is the mark of growth to continually test those proxies against reality,

778
00:42:42,840 --> 00:42:46,440
hunt for counterexamples, and repair the representations that have collapsed.

779
00:42:46,640 --> 00:42:51,760
As we wrap up this deep dive, I want to leave you with one final standalone idea to mull over.

780
00:42:52,180 --> 00:42:57,500
We spent this entire time talking about how AI models naturally collapse the concept of correctness

781
00:42:57,500 --> 00:43:01,420
into verbosity simply by observing biased training data.

782
00:43:01,420 --> 00:43:04,720
They conflate the appearance of hard work with actual intelligence.

783
00:43:04,980 --> 00:43:06,800
But what if we turn that lens around?

784
00:43:07,180 --> 00:43:08,040
Turn it around on us.

785
00:43:08,240 --> 00:43:08,400
Yeah.

786
00:43:08,940 --> 00:43:13,100
If an algorithm is structurally vulnerable to projection collapse,

787
00:43:13,400 --> 00:43:18,620
what massive projection collapses are humans currently making about artificial intelligence itself?

788
00:43:18,720 --> 00:43:19,540
Well, that's heavy.

789
00:43:20,220 --> 00:43:24,120
Are we as a society collectively staring at these models?

790
00:43:24,120 --> 00:43:31,460
Models that are explicitly trained to spit out highly structured, formal, lengthy, confident text

791
00:43:31,460 --> 00:43:36,620
and conflating that accidental output with the substance of true consciousness?

792
00:43:37,140 --> 00:43:41,360
Are we looking at the algorithmic equivalent of a padded high school essay and saying,

793
00:43:41,500 --> 00:43:46,520
wow, there's a soul in there, simply because those are the traits we accidentally associate with smart humans?

794
00:43:46,800 --> 00:43:49,240
We might just be reading the font size and margins.

795
00:43:49,480 --> 00:43:49,940
Exactly.

796
00:43:50,120 --> 00:43:51,120
It's a terrifying thought.

797
00:43:51,120 --> 00:43:56,480
Are we being fooled by the very verbosity that the AI engineers are desperately trying to repair?

798
00:43:56,960 --> 00:43:58,580
Thank you for taking this deep dive with us.

799
00:43:58,640 --> 00:44:00,580
Keep questioning the proxies you rely on.

800
00:44:00,880 --> 00:44:02,360
Keep looking for the counterexamples.

801
00:44:02,820 --> 00:44:07,740
And above all, make sure your own fibers of representation remain fully unapologetically expanded.

